=2Eorg/2015/01/28/mark-strand-creativity/?mc_cid=3D1ed92b7ada&mc_eid=3D[UNI=
QID]) (who is not related to the famed bookstore but is=2C via paternity=
=2C to the volume=E2=80=99s editor=2C Jessica Strand).

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0393352080/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D1ed=
92b7ada&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

Two generations after William Faulkner asserted in his Nobel Prize accepta=
nce speech (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/01/10/william-faulkner-nobe=
l-prize-acceptance-speech/?mc_cid=3D1ed92b7ada&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) that th=
e role of the writer is =E2=80=9Cto help man endure by lifting his heart=
=2C=E2=80=9D Saunders shares a reflection wonderfully countercultural amid=
 our era of marketable tragedy and rampant cynicism (https://www.brainpick=
ings.org/2016/05/16/annenberg-commencement/?mc_cid=3D1ed92b7ada&mc_eid=3D[=
UNIQID]) :

When I was younger=2C I was for some stupid reason really taken aback by t=
he realization that capitalism could be harsh. It had never occurred to me=
 before. So my work tended to be a little preoccupied with that notion=2C=
 maybe. My wife and I fell head over heels=2C and had our daughters pretty=
 quickly. Now we=E2=80=99ve been married for twenty-six years and our daug=
hters are grown up and wonderful. So lately my feeling is there ought to b=
e a place for some fictional corollary of the fact that sometimes things a=
ctually work=E2=80=A6 An artist can sometimes represent the idea that thin=
gs can be wonderful.

Responding to the observation that a line from a short story of his =E2=80=
=94 =E2=80=9CCan goodness win?=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 encapsulates an undergir=
ding concern across all of his work=2C Saunders adds:

Why not? Yes=2C it can win. But it can also lose =E2=80=94 can get humilia=
ted. It can also cause other people problems=2C by morphing into self-righ=
teousness. I think what a fiction writer does is represent different viewp=
oints vividly. And without necessarily seeming to prefer one over the othe=
r. =E2=80=9CCan goodness win?=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CYes=2C it does all the tim=
e.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CNo=2C it cannot: it loses all the time.=E2=80=9D Both=
 true.

[=E2=80=A6]

See how long you can stay in that space=2C where both things are true. You=
=2C little mind=2C actually don=E2=80=99t have to decide. That=E2=80=99s a=
 great place to try to be. And for a fiction writer=2C that=E2=80=99s the=
 best place to be: you=E2=80=99ve put two apparently opposing truths in th=
e air and you=E2=80=99re just letting them hang there=2C knowing that the=
 real truth is =E2=80=A6 that opposition.

In a sentiment that calls to mind Denise Levertov=E2=80=99s notion of the=
 midwifery of creative work (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/06/02/deni=
se-levertov-letters-creativity/?mc_cid=3D1ed92b7ada&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])=
 =2C Saunders suggests that even if one were to inhabit that opposition=2C=
 one can=E2=80=99t forcibly wrest out of it the sort of aliveness that mak=
es art. Rather than trying to will it=2C one ought to be willing to let it=
 come into a life of its own. He reflects on having this pivotal realizati=
on when he was starting out as a writer and finding his own voice:

I found out that the same minute I had an idea about what I wanted to writ=
e=2C life would go out of it. I=E2=80=99m a Bear of Little Brain=2C as Win=
nie the Pooh would say. My challenge is to try to keep the themes out of w=
hat I=E2=80=99m writing as long as possible=E2=80=A6 Einstein said it bett=
er: =E2=80=9CNo worthy problem is ever solved on the plane of its original=
 conception.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6 It=E2=80=99s got more integrity if it come=
s in of its own accord.

At the end of the event=2C in answering a reader=E2=80=99s question=2C Sau=
nders returns to the inherent duality of life and the notion that although=
 we=E2=80=99re animated by conflicting impulses and irrepressible moral im=
perfection=2C we can still live rich and beautiful lives. Echoing Parker P=
almer=E2=80=99s ennobling assertion that =E2=80=9Cwholeness does not mean=
 perfection: it means embracing brokenness as an integral part of life=2C=
=E2=80=9D (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/11/03/parker-palmer-hidden-w=
holeness/?mc_cid=3D1ed92b7ada&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) Saunders observes:

At any given moment you=E2=80=99re failing to see the way things actually=
 are. The manifestation is that you=E2=80=99re failing to be kind. You=E2=
=80=99re anxious. You=E2=80=99re neurotic. I don=E2=80=99t think it=E2=80=
=99s so much about external things. I think you could be a very happy=2C h=
igh-functioning person and still note the moment-to-moment failures.

Complement this particular portion of the wholly terrific Upstairs at the=
 Strand (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0393352080/braipick-20?mc_=
cid=3D1ed92b7ada&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =E2=80=94 a trove of unscripted wisdo=
m on literature and life from of the greatest writers of our time =E2=80=
=94 with George Saunders=E2=80=99s moving commencement address about the p=
ower of kindness (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/04/28/george-saunders=
-on-kindness-animated/?mc_cid=3D1ed92b7ada&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C then re=
visit this evolving library of notable wisdom on writing (https://www.brai=
npickings.org/2013/05/03/advice-on-writing/?mc_cid=3D1ed92b7ada&mc_eid=3D[=
UNIQID]) =2C including Hemingway=E2=80=99s advice to young writers (https=
://www.brainpickings.org/2016/01/04/with-hemingway-arnold-samuelson-writin=
g/?mc_cid=3D1ed92b7ada&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Virginia Woolf on writing a=
nd self-doubt (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/02/25/virginia-woolf-wri=
ting-self-doubt/?mc_cid=3D1ed92b7ada&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Ann Patchett=
