** The Science of Affection: How a Rebel Researcher Pioneered the Study of=
 Love in the 1950s and Illuminated How Parents Shape Children=E2=80=99s Em=
otional Patterns (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/07/07/love-at-goon-pa=
rk-harry-harlow-deborah-blum/?mc_cid=3D1ed92b7ada&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])
------------------------------------------------------------

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/046502601X/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D1ed=
92b7ada&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

=E2=80=9CWho we are and who we become depends=2C in part=2C on whom we lov=
e=2C=E2=80=9D psychologists Thomas Lewis=2C Fari Amini=2C and Richard Lann=
on observed in their indispensable A General Theory of Love (https://www.b=
rainpickings.org/2012/06/25/limbic-revision/?mc_cid=3D1ed92b7ada&mc_eid=3D=
[UNIQID]) . =E2=80=9CTo love without knowing how to love wounds the perso=
n we love=2C=E2=80=9D the great Zen teacher Thich Nhat Hahn wrote (https:/=
/www.brainpickings.org/2015/03/31/how-to-love-thich-nhat-hanh/?mc_cid=3D1e=
d92b7ada&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . But although love has been a fixture of phi=
losophy=2C ethics=2C and the world=E2=80=99s great spiritual traditions si=
nce the dawn of recorded thought=2C it has earned its place as a subject o=
f science only recently=2C and chiefly thanks to one man =E2=80=94 primate=
 researcher Harry Harlow (October 31=2C 1905=E2=80=93December 6=2C 1981)=
=2C who defied the scientific dogma of his day to unravel the psychologica=
l armature of affection=2C how our formative attachments shape who we beco=
me=2C and why love is the most primary need to be met for healthy developm=
ent.

In the immeasurably captivating Love at Goon Park: Harry Harlow and the Sc=
ience of Affection (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/046502601X/brai=
pick-20?mc_cid=3D1ed92b7ada&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) (public library (http://ww=
w.worldcat.org/title/love-at-goon-park-harry-harlow-and-the-science-of-aff=
ection/oclc/50763066&referer=3Dbrief_results?mc_cid=3D1ed92b7ada&mc_eid=3D=
[UNIQID]) )=2C Pulitzer-winning writer Deborah Blum chronicles the trailb=
lazing work and far-reaching legacy of this =E2=80=9Cchainsmoking=2C poetr=
y-writing=2C alcoholic=2C impossible genius of a psychologist=E2=80=9D =E2=
=80=94 a =E2=80=9Cstubborn=2C scruffy=2C middle-aged researcher =E2=80=A6=
 who happens to believe that his profession is wrong and doesn=E2=80=99t m=
ind saying so=2C=E2=80=9D a man who =E2=80=9Clives at the lab=2C dawn to d=
ark=2C fueled by coffee=2C cigarettes=2C alcohol=2C and obsession.=E2=80=
=9D

Harlow=E2=80=99s point of obsession and insurgency was the conviction=2C b=
oldly defiant of the era=E2=80=99s scientific dogma=2C that love matters=
 =E2=80=94 that it is a centerpiece of our psychoemotional constitution an=
d=2C as such=2C merits being systematically studied rather than dismissed=
 as an irrelevant and unscientific whim. Indeed=2C the book is as much a b=
iography of Harlow himself as it is of this astonishingly nascent idea=2C=
 which was scientific anathema in Harlow=E2=80=99s heyday but has steered=
 the course of social science and permeated popular culture in the half-ce=
ntury since.

Harry Harlow observes a baby monkey interacting with a cloth mother

Harlow used the 120 rhesus monkey in his lab to study mother-infant attach=
ment and how the effects of maternal separation and social isolation illum=
inate the nature of love. His most famous experiment devised two versions=
 of an artificial surrogate mother for the baby monkeys =E2=80=94 one made=
 entirely of wire and the other=2C designed to be cozy and cuddly=2C of wi=
re and cloth; both were internally heated to simulate the warmth of a real=
 mother=E2=80=99s body. The empirical hook was that the wire-only mother h=
eld a bottle of milk=2C which the babies could feed on=2C whereas the cudd=
ly mother offered nothing but the creaturely comfort of warmth and soft to=
uch.

Upending decades=2C if not centuries=2C of prior theories predicated on a=
 kind of survivalist evolutionary pragmatism=2C Harlow found that the baby=
 monkeys consistently chose the cuddly mother over the feeding but cold mo=
ther. They lived latched onto the cloth mother and leaned over to the wire=
 one nearby to take a sip of milk only when they grew hungry=2C but even a=
s they did this=2C they remained completely attached =E2=80=94 both litera=
lly and figuratively =E2=80=94 to the cuddly robot. Over and other=2C the=
 monkeys demonstrated that the safe embrace of comfort is more vital to th=
eir development than the steady but cold supply of sustenance.

Harlow=E2=80=99s findings were as profound as they are disquieting=2C part=
icularly to those of us who are the product of far from perfect parenting.=
 Recounting his central assertion =E2=80=94 which he made on national tele=
vision=2C further defying the norms of his profession =E2=80=94 Blum write=
s:

We begin our lives with love [and] we learn human connection at home. It=
 is the foundation upon which we build our lives =E2=80=94 or it should be=
 =E2=80=94 and if the monkey or the human doesn=E2=80=99t learn love in in=
fancy=2C he or she =E2=80=9Cmay never learn to love at all.=E2=80=9D

=E2=80=9CIf monkeys have taught us anything=2C=E2=80=9D Harlow asserted in=
 reflecting on his experiments=2C =E2=80=9Cit=E2=80=99s that you=E2=80=99v=
e got to learn how to love before you learn how to live.=E2=80=9D Today=2C=
 his findings are revered by developmental psychologists=2C his methods re=
viled by animal rights advocates in light of our radically different norms=
 of primate research=2C and his legacy as enormous and messy as the subjec=
t of his study.

Art by Isol from Daytime Visions (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/05/25=
/daytime-visions-isol/?mc_cid=3D1ed92b7ada&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])

To appreciate just how radical a departure from the status quo of science=
 Harlow=E2=80=99s theories were=2C we must turn to language =E2=80=94 for=
=2C as the poet Elizabeth Alexander memorably observed=2C =E2=80=9Cwe live=
 in the word.=E2=80=9D (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/05/24/elizabeth=
-alexander-power-and-possibility-writing/?mc_cid=3D1ed92b7ada&mc_eid=3D[U=
NIQID]) Harlow=E2=80=99s work was his life=2C and he refused to live in li=
miting language defined by dogma. Blum captures his irreverent genius:

Professor Harlow has already been asked to correct his language: He=E2=80=
=99s been instructed on the correct term for a close relationship. Why can=
=E2=80=99t he just say =E2=80=9Cproximity=E2=80=9D like everyone else? Som=
ehow the word =E2=80=9Clove=E2=80=9D just keeps springing to his lips when=
 he talks about parents and children=2C friends and partners. He=E2=80=99s=
 been known to lose his temper when discussing it. =E2=80=9CPerhaps all yo=
u=E2=80=99ve known in life is proximity=2C=E2=80=9D he once snapped at a v=
isitor to his lab at the University of Wisconsin in Madison. =E2=80=9CI th=
ank God I=E2=80=99ve known more.=E2=80=9D

[=E2=80=A6]

Who wouldn=E2=80=99t believe that love was=2C at its best=2C a safe harbor=
 =E2=80=94 a parent=E2=80=99s arm scooping up a frightened child=2C holdin=
g it heart to heart? It=E2=80=99s hard to believe=2C in retrospect=2C how=
 many powerful scientists opposed this idea.

Blum points to one researcher emblematic of the era =E2=80=94 psychologist=
 John B. Watson=2C president of the American Psychological Association=2C=
 who believed that emotion was a moral weakness to be controlled and consi=
dered love=2C the most intense and messiest of the emotions=2C a supreme o=
ffender the corrupting effects of which should be restrained as early as p=
ossible. In a particularly spirited passage=2C he admonished:

When you are tempted to pet your child remember that mother love is a dang=
erous instrument=E2=80=A6 Once a child=E2=80=99s character has been spoile=
d by bad handling=2C which can be done in a few days=2C who can say that t=
he damage is ever repaired?

In the midst of this professional climate=2C Harlow chose =E2=80=9Cto stan=
d on behalf of that improbable=2C unreliable=2C elusive emotion called lov=
e=E2=80=9D and helmed a quiet=2C monumental revolution. It=E2=80=99s aston=
ishing to consider that getting science to heed a truth this elemental and=
 intuitive =E2=80=94 that love is central to our experience of being human=
 =E2=80=94 should necessitate nothing short of a revolution=2C and yet it=
 very much did. Like any revolution=2C it required the collusion of kindre=
d spirits working together against an enormous tide of pushback.

Art by Isol from The Menino (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/12/09/the-=
menino-isol/?mc_cid=3D1ed92b7ada&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])

Among those confederates was the English psychologist John Bowlby=2C who p=
ioneered attachment theory and the idea that the fulfillment of physical n=
eeds like sustenance and shelter is a secondary drive in the parent-child=
 relationship =E2=80=94 love is the primary one. Blum explains:

What attachment theory essentially says is that being loved matters =E2=80=
=94 and=2C more than that=2C it matters who loves us and whom we love in r=
eturn. It=E2=80=99s not just a matter of the warm body holding the bottle;=
 it=E2=80=99s not object love at all; we love specific people and we need=
 them to love us back. And in the case of the child=E2=80=99s tie to the m=
other=2C it matters that the mother loves that baby and that the baby know=
s it. When you are a very small child=2C love needs to be as tangible as w=
arm arms around you and as audible as the lull of a gentle voice at night.

Bowlby=E2=80=99s work was instrumental=2C but there was one other essentia=
l building block in the architecture of Harlow=E2=80=99s quiet revolution=
 =E2=80=94 the work of a New York physician named William Goldfarb=2C who=
 made the unnerving discovery that parental affection exerts a strong infl=
uence on the child=E2=80=99s IQ. Preoccupied with the fate of children in=
 New York=E2=80=99s Jewish orphanages and foundling homes=2C Goldfarb had=
 grown concerned that social isolation was damaging their intellectual dev=
elopment. To test his theory=2C he measured their performance on IQ tests=
 and compared it to that of children in foster homes.

Foundling children were often the result of unwanted pregnancies by educat=
ed women of high social class=2C whereas foster kids came from less creden=
tialed backgrounds and ended up with their new parents after the displacem=
ent or death of their biological parents. Since existing theories held tha=
t genes were the greatest predictor of intelligence=2C it was expected tha=
t the foundlings would perform better than the foster kids on IQ tests. Bu=
t Goldfarb found the opposite. Love and intelligence=2C it turned out=2C w=
ere far more strongly correlated than genetics and intelligence.

Art by Soyeon Kim from Wild Ideas (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/07/1=
3/wild-ideas-kelsey-kim/?mc_cid=3D1ed92b7ada&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) by Elin K=
elsey

Blum writes:

The foundlings were less determined=2C less interested=2C less willing to=
 explore=E2=80=A6 One problem was that no one was interested in them=2C [=
Goldfarb] said. The caretakers seemed indifferent. But was that surprising=
? Goldfarb asked. Is an adult ever interested in a child who doesn=E2=80=
=99t stir his heart? An odd kind of chicken or egg issue underlies that qu=
ery. Does affection for another person create interest in him or does inte=
rest lead to affection?

When it came to the foundlings=2C Goldfarb had an idea that interest and a=
ffection twined together=2C tight as a rope=2C almost inseparably. All of=
 us=2C even as babies=2C are a bundle of feelings and desires=2C he said.=
 Our positive emotions grow best in an interactive sense=2C fostered by ho=
w we react to others and how they respond to us. A baby=2C a child=2C even=
 an adult=2C needs at least one person interested and responsive. We grow=
 best in soil cultivated by someone who thinks we matter.

This brings us back to Harlow. Building on these compelling but fragmentar=
y insights=2C he advanced a robust and holistic theory of how profoundly o=
ur formative interactions and attachments shape our destiny=2C and then he=
 set out to derive definitive evidence. To prove the importance of parenta=
l affection=2C he would demonstrate the effects of its absence and=2C even=
 more dramatically=2C of its opposite.

Blum chronicles the clever=2C if cruel=2C twist Harlow put on his wire-mot=
her experiments:

The lab team built what Harry called evil or =E2=80=9Cmonster=E2=80=9D mot=
hers. There were four of them and they were cloth moms gone crazy. All of=
 them had a soft-centered body for cuddling. But they were=2C all of them=
=2C booby traps. One was a =E2=80=9Cshaking=E2=80=9D mother who rocked so=
 violently that=2C Harry said=2C the teeth and bones of the infant chatter=
ed in unison. The second was an air-blast mother. She blew compressed air=
 against the infant with such force that the baby looked=2C Harry said=2C=
 as if it would be denuded. The third had an embedded steel frame that=2C=
 on schedule or demand=2C would fling forward and hurl the infant monkey o=
ff the mother=E2=80=99s body. The fourth monster mother had brass spikes (=
blunt-tipped) tucked into her chest; these would suddenly=2C unexpectedly=
 push against the clinging child.

What Harlow found was both heartbreaking and heartbreakingly understandabl=
e =E2=80=94 rather than fleeing from the monstrous mothers=2C the babies t=
ried harder to earn their affection. After every violent repulsion=2C they=
 returned to the monsters=2C only to cling more tightly and coo more besee=
chingly=2C =E2=80=9Cexpressing faith and love as if all were forgiven=2C=
=E2=80=9D as Harlow put it.

Art by Owen Davey from Mad About Monkeys (https://www.brainpickings.org/20=
15/08/26/mad-about-monkeys-owen-davey/?mc_cid=3D1ed92b7ada&mc_eid=3D[UNIQ=
ID])

Blum encapsulates the profound implications=2C revealing love to be a kind=
 of primal addiction:

No experiment could have better demonstrated the depth and strength of a b=
aby=E2=80=99s addiction for her parent. Or how terrifyingly vulnerable tha=
t addiction makes a child. These little monkeys would be frightened away b=
y brass spike mom =E2=80=94 and yet it was she they turned to for comfort.=
 They had to; she was what they had. Here indeed was further evidence of t=
hat haven-of-security effect=2C for better and for worse. It doesn=E2=80=
=99t always keep you safe. If your mother is your only source of comfort a=
nd your mother is evil=2C what choices are left you in seeking safe harbor=
? No choice except to keep trying to cast anchor in the only harbor availa=
ble.

Harry and his team would find the same pattern when real mother monkeys we=
re rejecting or abusive. The scientists marveled at =E2=80=9Cthe desperate=
 efforts the babies made to contact their mothers. No matter how abusive t=
he mothers were=2C the babies persisted in returning.=E2=80=9D They return=
ed more often=2C they reached and clung and coaxed far more frequently tha=
n the children of normal mothers. The infants were so preoccupied with eng=
aging their mothers that they had little energy for friends. The clinging=
 babies=E2=80=99 energy was directed into their attempts to coax a little=
 affection out at home. Sometimes the real monkey mothers did respond=2C g=
radually=2C more kindly. But while trying to reach mother=2C the little mo=
nkeys never had time to reach anyone else.

Harlow=E2=80=99s findings ushered in a tidal wave of change in psychology=
 and instituted love as a proper and central subject in the study of human=
 development. Generations of psychologists built on his work=2C including=
 many of Harlow=E2=80=99s own students.

Among them was Steve Suomi=2C director of the National Institutes of Healt=
h lab of comparative ethology=2C who became interested in the interplay of=
 nature and nurture in emotional development. In one ingenious experiment=
=2C he divided a sample of baby monkeys into two groups. Some remained wit=
h their biological mothers=2C who were selected to be unaffectionate and i=
nattentive=2C while others were raised by what Suomi called =E2=80=9Csuper=
moms=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 caretakers selected for their exceedingly affectio=
nate nurturing style. Both groups of mothers cared for a variety of babies=
=2C including some naturally anxious and nervous ones.

Suomi found that the baby monkeys developed optimally under the care of th=
e most loving mother=2C regardless of their biological connection. The eff=
ects were most dramatic on the nervous babies =E2=80=94 with an unwavering=
ly affectionate mother=2C they grew calmer and became nurturers themselves=
=2C but with a neurotic mother=2C they grew even more nervous=2C fearful=
=2C and anxious to explore their environment.

Blum writes:

There are several reminders in that elegant NIH experiment: that we need n=
ot grow up to be our mothers; that we may not want to; that it=E2=80=99s n=
ot easy to change. And that it may be unfair to load all our expectations=
 and needs onto one parent=2C anyway. With the best intentions in the worl=
d=2C one person may not be able =E2=80=94 or intended =E2=80=94 to give a=
 child everything he or she needs. The extended family=2C even the right c=
hild care provider may be exactly what=E2=80=99s needed.

As it turns out=2C this is true not only of parent-child relationships but=
 of all intimate attachments =E2=80=94 Esther Perel has written elegantly=
 (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0060753641/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D1=
ed92b7ada&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) about the comparable perils of placing all o=
f one=E2=80=99s expectations on one=E2=80=99s romantic partner. But since=
 we seek out romantic partners largely on the basis of emotional patternin=
g laid out in childhood (https://www.brainpickings.org/2012/03/02/characte=
r-personality/?mc_cid=3D1ed92b7ada&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C even this can b=
e traced to Harlow=E2=80=99s legacy.

Blum encapsulates the heart of his work and its enduring implications:

There is no requirement for angelic perfection in parenting. The requireme=
nt is just to stay in there. Harry=E2=80=99s research tells us that love i=
s work. So do all the studies that follow. The nature of love is about pay=
ing attention to the people who matter=2C about still giving when you are=
 too tired to give. Be a mother who listens=2C a father who cuddles=2C a f=
riend who calls back=2C a helping neighbor=2C a loving child.

That emphasis on love in our everyday lives may be the best of that quiet=
 revolution in psychology=2C the one that changed the way we think about l=
ove and relationship almost without our noticing that had happened. We tak=
e for granted now that parents should hug their children=2C that relations=
hips are worth the time=2C that taking care of each other is part of the g=
ood life. It is such a good foundation that it=E2=80=99s almost astonishin=
g to consider how recent it is. For that foundation under our feet we owe=
 a debt to Harry Harlow and to all the scientists who believed and worked=
 toward a psychology of the heart.

At the end=2C in Harry=E2=80=99s handiwork=2C there=E2=80=99s nothing sent=
imental about love=2C no sunlit clouds and glory notes=E2=80=94it=E2=80=99=
s a substantial=2C earthbound connection=2C grounded in effort=2C kindness=
=2C and decency. Learning to love=2C Harry liked to say=2C is really about=
 learning to live. Perhaps everyday affection seems a small facet of love.=
 Perhaps=2C though=2C it is the modest=2C steady responses that see us thr=
ough day after day=2C that stretch into a life of close and loving relatio=
nships. Or=2C as Harry Harlow wrote to a friend=2C =E2=80=9CPerhaps one sh=
ould always be modest when talking about love.=E2=80=9D

Love at Goon Park (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/046502601X/braip=
ick-20?mc_cid=3D1ed92b7ada&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) is a tremendously pleasurab=
le and revelatory read in its totality. Complement it with young Barack Ob=
ama on what his mother taught him about love (https://www.brainpickings.or=
g/2016/06/13/barack-obama-dreams-from-my-father-love/?mc_cid=3D1ed92b7ada&=
mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Iris Murdoch on how love gives meaning to human ex=
istence (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/02/24/iris-murdoch-causality-c=
hance-love/?mc_cid=3D1ed92b7ada&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C and Erich Fromm on=
