selves=2C=E2=80=9D wrote Israel Rosenfield in his landmark exploration of=
 consciousness (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/03/17/the-strange-famil=
iar-and-forgotten-israel-rosenfield/?mc_cid=3D1ed92b7ada&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID=
]) a century later.

Much of this hiding=2C neuroscientist Antonio Damasio argues in his revela=
tory 1999 book The Feeling of What Happens: Body and Emotion in the Making=
 of Consciousness (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0156010755/braip=
ick-20?mc_cid=3D1ed92b7ada&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) (public library (http://www=
=2Eworldcat.org/title/feeling-of-what-happens-body-and-emotion-in-the-making=
-of-consciousness/oclc/41070953&referer=3Dbrief_results?mc_cid=3D1ed92b7ad=
a&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) )=2C stems from a chronic mistrust between the mind=
 and the body =E2=80=94 amid the seething cauldron of sensation and percep=
tion that we call consciousness=2C we somehow fog our mental view of our v=
ery own bodily selves.

Art from Neurocomic (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/04/02/neurocomic-n=
obrow/?mc_cid=3D1ed92b7ada&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C a graphic novel about h=
ow the brain works

Damasio writes:

Sometimes we use our minds not to discover facts=2C but to hide them. We u=
se part of the mind as a screen to prevent another part of it from sensing=
 what goes on elsewhere. The screening is not necessarily intentional =E2=
=80=94 we are not deliberate obfuscators all of the time =E2=80=94 but del=
iberate or not=2C the screen does hide.

One of the things the screen hides most effectively is the body=2C our own=
 body=2C by which I mean the ins of it=2C its interiors. Like a veil throw=
n over the skin to secure its modesty=2C the screen partially removes from=
 the mind the inner states of the body=2C those that constitute the flow o=
f life as it wanders in the journey of each day.

The alleged vagueness=2C elusiveness=2C and intangibility of emotions and=
 feelings are probably symptoms of this fact=2C an indication of how we co=
ver the representation of our bodies=2C of how much mental imagery based o=
n nonbody objects and events masks the reality of the body. Otherwise we w=
ould easily know that emotions and feelings are tangibly about the body. S=
ometimes we use our minds to hide a part of our beings from another part o=
f our beings.

Complement this particular fragment of the wholly excellent The Feeling of=
 What Happens (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0156010755/braipick-=
20?mc_cid=3D1ed92b7ada&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) with the late=2C great=2C pione=
ering memory researcher Suzanne Corkin on how memory colludes with us in t=
his obfuscation (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/06/08/permanent-presen=
t-tense-suzanne-corkin-h-m/?mc_cid=3D1ed92b7ada&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) and ps=
ychiatrist Bessel van der Kolk on the science of how our minds and our bod=
ies converge in the healing of trauma (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/=
06/20/the-body-keeps-the-score-van-der-kolk/?mc_cid=3D1ed92b7ada&mc_eid=3D=
[UNIQID]) =2C then revisit Rilke on the relationship between the body and=
 the spirit (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/08/07/rilke-on-body-and-so=
ul/?mc_cid=3D1ed92b7ada&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) .


