oes on elsewhere. The screening is not necessarily intentional =E2=80=94 w=
e are not deliberate obfuscators all of the time =E2=80=94 but deliberate=
 or not=2C the screen does hide. </p><p style=3D"-webkit-text-size-adjust:=
 100%;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;color: #808080;font-family: Arial=2C Sans=
-serif;font-size: 14px;line-height: 170%;text-align: left;">One of the thi=
ngs the screen hides most effectively is the body=2C our own body=2C by wh=
ich I mean the ins of it=2C its interiors. Like a veil thrown over the ski=
n to secure its modesty=2C the screen partially removes from the mind the=
 inner states of the body=2C those that constitute the flow of life as it=
 wanders in the journey of each day.</p><p style=3D"-webkit-text-size-adju=
st: 100%;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;color: #808080;font-family: Arial=2C S=
ans-serif;font-size: 14px;line-height: 170%;text-align: left;">The alleged=
 vagueness=2C elusiveness=2C and intangibility of emotions and feelings ar=
e probably symptoms of this fact=2C an indication of how we cover the repr=
esentation of our bodies=2C of how much mental imagery based on nonbody ob=
jects and events masks the reality of the body. Otherwise we would easily=
 know that emotions and feelings are tangibly about the body. Sometimes we=
 use our minds to hide a part of our beings from another part of our being=
s.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;-ms-text-siz=
e-adjust: 100%;color: #262626;font-family: Georgia=2C serif;font-size: 15p=
x;line-height: 175%;text-align: left;">Complement this particular fragment=
